4. Baptism.

The “elect '’ were present at the solemn vigil of Easter. The lections2 chosen for the occasion were meant to present a summary of the relations between man and God, and to form, as it were, a final instruction at the moment of the accomplishment of the mystery of initiation. These lections are practically the same in all the Latin rituals. Some of the finest passages in the Old Testament are presented in them—such as the account of the Creation, the Deluge, the Sacrifice of Isaac, the Passage of the Red Sea, the Vision of Ezekiel, the History of Jonah, the account of the image set up by Nebuchadnezzar; then some passages from the prophets, as, for instance, that in which Tsaiah predicts baptism, and extols the vine of the Lord3 also that dealing with the covenant of Moses and the institution of the Passover.
